\subsection{Rejection sampling and the conditional prior}
\label{sec:loss-bias}

The Model~A prior is conditional on perturbative validity, implemented by rejection sampling (Section~\ref{sec:model-a}). Approximately $33\%$ of unconditioned log-uniform draws are rejected because the resulting spectra produce pathological QCD configurations (charm-bottom thresholds too close, $\alpha_s$ blow-up, etc.) for which the running prescription is ill-posed. We verify that the conditioning is well-behaved by two diagnostics on the implementation, and note one earlier diagnostic that we no longer rely on.

\paragraph{Rejection-sampling reframe consistency check.} We re-implemented Model~A as explicit rejection sampling: continue drawing from the unconditioned log-uniform prior until $N = 10{,}000$ retained valid spectra are obtained (acceptance rate $\approx 67.6\%$). The resulting tail fractions agree with the conditional-prior implementation within MC noise: the maximum absolute difference across the nine claims is $0.020$ (driven by MC noise at a different random seed), with the running claims agreeing to within $0.01$ and the full-search tail fraction agreeing to within $0.002$. The two implementations are mathematically equivalent and the conditional-prior framing is therefore not implementation-sensitive.

\paragraph{Engine-switching crosscheck.} We re-ran Model~A using 2-loop CRunDec in place of 4-loop, on paired draws ($N = 10{,}000$). The rejected set is identical: the same $3{,}269$ draws are rejected at both loop orders, confirming that perturbative validity is intrinsic to the mass spectrum and not specific to the loop order. We additionally re-ran Model~A using a pure-Python analytic 1-loop running scheme (closed-form $\alpha_s(\mu)$ with simplified threshold matching), which has substantially lower rejection rate ($13.4\%$) because the simpler matching tolerates configurations that full CRunDec cannot handle. Under the analytic 1-loop scheme the full-search tail fraction is $\approx 0.37$ versus $\approx 0.50$ under 4-loop CRunDec. The difference is comparable in magnitude to the loop-order spread documented in Section~\ref{sec:loop-order} and is consistent with the interpretation that the two schemes are sampling slightly different conditional priors (their respective perturbative-validity regions differ).

\paragraph{Diagnostic not used.} An earlier draft compared the distribution of best residuals between rejected and retained draws using the surrogate running scheme to assess whether the rejection set was biased. We do not rely on that diagnostic in the current analysis because the surrogate did not reproduce full-CRunDec results at the per-draw level (Section~\ref{sec:surrogate-validation}), so a comparison routed through the surrogate is not informative about the conditional prior implemented with full CRunDec. The two diagnostics above use exact full-CRunDec computations on the rejection-sampled prior and are not subject to that concern.

\paragraph{Summary.} The Model~A reported tail fractions are conditional on the perturbatively-valid log-uniform prior, implemented by rejection. The conditioning is an explicit feature of the reference class, not a missing-data problem; the rejection-sampling reframe gives identical tail fractions; and the conditioning is engine-independent within CRunDec. The qualitative ranking of claims is preserved across all alternative implementations of the perturbative-validity condition.



\subsection{Loop-order convergence of the observed Koide combination}
\label{sec:loop-order}

To assess the sensitivity of Model~A tail probabilities to the perturbative order of the running implementation, we re-ran Model~A at 1-loop, 2-loop, 3-loop, 4-loop, and 5-loop CRunDec on identical paired draws ($N = 10{,}000$). For \emph{self-scale} claims (those evaluated at $\mu = m_i$ without inter-flavor running, including Cao $(c,b,t)$, Rivero $(s,c,b)$, and the chain-no-run and 20-triple self families), the tail probabilities are stable to four decimal places across all loop orders, as expected: these claims do not invoke running across flavor thresholds and the loop-order choice does not change their numerical evaluation.

For \emph{running} claims, the picture is more subtle. The tail probabilities at $\{1, 3, 4, 5\}$ loops cluster within a spread of $\approx 0.05$--$0.13$, with 4-loop and 5-loop closest to each other, indicating perturbative convergence at the higher orders. The 2-loop result is anomalous: the full-search tail probability returns $0.037$ at 2-loop versus $\{0.57, 0.63, 0.50, 0.53\}$ at $\{1, 3, 4, 5\}$ loops respectively. Diagnostics show this is not a null-distribution pathology. The 2-loop \emph{observed} value is itself not converged: at 2-loop, $m_c(m_\tau) = 1.159$~GeV with $|Q - 2/3| = 5.1 \times 10^{-4}$, versus $m_c(m_\tau) = 1.143$~GeV with $|Q - 2/3| = 5.1 \times 10^{-5}$ at 4-loop. The 2-loop observed Koide residual is an order of magnitude larger than at higher loop orders. This worse observed value is more easily beaten by random-spectrum draws in the 2-loop matched null, yielding a small tail probability that is internally consistent at 2-loop but reflects that the Koide closure is itself a higher-loop phenomenon. We exclude 2-loop from the convergence assessment on this basis: it is not a misbehaving null but a perturbative order at which the observed quantity has not converged.

The remaining 1/3/4/5-loop convergence pattern (full-search tail probabilities in $[0.50, 0.63]$) shows the absolute Model~A tail probabilities for running claims to be stable at the $\sim 0.05$--$0.13$ level across well-converged loop orders, comparable to the prior-class systematic from Section~\ref{sec:prior-sensitivity} and substantially smaller than the broader scope-of-reference-class question discussed in Section~\ref{sec:model-a}. The $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ baseline tail probability returns $\{0.003, 0.005, 0.002, 0.004\}$ at orders $\{1, 3, 4, 5\}$---a spread of $\approx 0.003$, all values within the same order of magnitude and all firmly below $0.01$. The $(c,b,t)$ all-signs-with-running family returns $\{0.010, 0.013, 0.007, 0.013\}$. Across all running claims and across the four-orders set, the qualitative ranking is preserved.

All Model~A numbers reported in the main text and Table~\ref{tab:pvalues} use 4-loop running, which is the conventional standard for $\overline{\text{MS}}$ quark mass running.



